Ten years—that’s how long it had been since her brother, Gōsuke (剛介), went missing. He had vanished along with a specialist team of scientists and military personnel who entered the Tokyo exclusion zone.

Now she stood on the decaying remains of the street where she and her brother had grown up. Her former home loomed ahead, unchanged except for the encroaching greenery slowly reclaiming the concrete metropolis.

Streetlights still glowed after all this time. But their flicker was more than nostalgic—it was a warning. She needed to find shelter soon. These old city streets were no safe haven for someone alone, let alone a well-supplied and armed team. Her childhood home might yet serve as a safe house for her expeditions deeper into the city.

They were once ordinary places—suburbs tucked between hills, where porch lights flickered on at dusk and children raced down quiet streets. But when the outbreak reached the outer districts, the silence became permanent.

Evacuation orders came fast. Families left behind meals still warm, laundry half-folded, and birthday decorations fluttering in the wind. The infected moved like a tide—slow at first, then relentless. Power grids failed. Communications went dark. The last broadcasts warned of containment breaches and urged citizens to flee inland.

Now, nature creeps back in. Ivy climbs the walls of empty homes. Birds nest in broken attics. The towns stand frozen in time, haunted not by screams—but by the absence of them. Survivors call them The Silent Towns, markers of a world that unraveled street by street.

Some say the infected still wander there, drawn to the echoes of memory. Others believe the towns are cursed, left untouched by scavengers and search teams alike. But one thing is certain: no one who returns stays long.

A very high-quality digital illustration in a fixed, signature style—sharp, expressive inky linework with varied weight; stylized-realistic anatomy; layered cell+soft shading; high micro-contrast; cinematic lighting with restrained bloom and a clean rim light; ethereal atmospheric depth; ornate surface textures; filmic tonemapping; crystal-clear edges (not painterly, not grainy). Landscape composition with dynamic diagonals. Two full-body elemental dragons face each other, each confined to its half of the frame with clean negative space between their muzzles.

Left: a dominant Ice dragon, body carved from translucent blue ice with frosted facets; crystalline horns, saw-tooth dorsal spines, and plate-like scales; breath exhaling glittering spindrift; hoarfrost clinging to talons; cool inner subsurface glow in the chest; eyes pale and luminous.

Right: a submissive Fire dragon, bowing low; anatomy formed from living flame veined through dark basalt/obsidian plates; ember freckles drifting from the flanks; faint heat-shimmer around edges; a heavy black-iron collar with rivets catching the rim light.

Ground: a central summoning circle etched into bedrock—thin hoarfrost on the left, vitrified glass and glowing cracks on the right; a narrow seam of hissing steam where ice and fire meet; runes are ornamental/non-readable. Random enhancing elements: aurora band and star-motes over the left sky, ash sparks over the right, scattered crystalline shrubs on the ice side, slag pebbles on the fire side.

Lighting & materials: key from above-center with teal fill on the left and amber key on the right; crisp speculars on ice facets, metal collar, and obsidian plates; AO in wing joints and scale overlaps; controlled bloom only on hottest edges.

Color & constraints: clean teal/blue vs amber/orange separation; no muddy midtones. SFW. Exclude text/watermarks/UI; exclude extra limbs/fingers; no blur, overbloom, banding, posterization, noise, or low detail.
